WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.200
[Amit Varma]: Among the many things we take for granted, there is money. We behave as if the system

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:15.120
[Amit Varma]: of money around us has always been there, as if it's as natural as the oxygen in the

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:20.120
[Amit Varma]: air. We behave as if a rupee tomorrow will be worth the same as a rupee today. In fact,

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:24.920
[Amit Varma]: we behave as if the financial system around us is stable and immutable, taking it for

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:30.520
[Amit Varma]: granted in the same way that we take the circulatory system of our body for granted. We don't think

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:35.720
[Amit Varma]: about our heart ceaselessly pumping blood until there is a problem with it. And when

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:54.240
[Unknown]: there is, that problem can become life-threatening.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:58.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen. My subject for today is our ongoing banking crisis and

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:04.000
[Amit Varma]: my guest is Tamal Bandopadhyay, author of the superb book, Pandemonium, The Great Indian

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.200
[Amit Varma]: Banking Tragedy. India has been in a financial crisis for a while now, our banking system

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:15.200
[Amit Varma]: is damaged, we have an NPA problem and this whole mess is a structural issue beyond any

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:19.920
[Amit Varma]: specific political party or government. I've done many episodes on different aspects of

00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:23.840
[Amit Varma]: this and they'll all be linked from the show notes. And if you care about this subject,

00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:30.080
[Amit Varma]: you must read Pandemonium. Tamal is India's most highly regarded banking columnist. He

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.880
[Amit Varma]: was part of the founding team of the newspaper Mint. He has held senior editorial positions

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:40.400
[Amit Varma]: in various newspapers and he's written a number of exceptional books. Pandemonium is particularly

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:45.080
[Amit Varma]: enjoyable because it's like many books in one. It features riveting storytelling with

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:50.760
[Amit Varma]: colourful tales of wild frauds and evocative scenes from Arthur Road Jail. It features

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:56.040
[Amit Varma]: incisive analysis in simple language that will make you feel like an expert at the end

00:01:56.040 --> 00:02:00.880
[Amit Varma]: of the book. It features long interviews with four ex-central bankers C. Rangarajan, Y.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:05.960
[Amit Varma]: V. Reddy, D. Subbarao and Raghuram Rajan, which alone are worth the price of the book

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: for their insights and their self-aware criticism. I was delighted when Tamal joined me on the

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.560
[Amit Varma]: scene and the unseen. And for me, honestly, the most rewarding part of this conversation

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:20.200
[Amit Varma]: came before we even started talking about banking. Listen in and I'm sure you'll agree

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:24.520
[Amit Varma]: with me. But before we get to our conversation, let's take a quick commercial break.

